# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: log-splitter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A **3D scanner** can be based on many different technologies, each with its own limitations, advantages and costs.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Many limitations in the kind of objects that can be digitized are still present.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] For example, optical technology may encounter difficulties with dark, shiny, reflective or transparent objects while industrial computed tomography scanning, structured-light 3D scanners, LiDAR and Time-Of-Flight 3D scanners can be used to construct digital 3D models, without destructive testing.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Collected 3D data is useful for a wide variety of applications.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] These devices are used extensively by the entertainment industry in the production of movies and video games, including virtual reality.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Other common applications of this technology include augmented reality, motion capture, gesture recognition, robotic mapping, industrial design, orthotics and prosthetics, reverse engineering and prototyping, quality control/inspection and the digitization of cultural artifacts.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The purpose of a 3D scanner is usually to create a 3D model.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] This 3D model consists of a polygon mesh or point cloud of geometric samples on the surface of the subject.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] These points can then be used to extrapolate the shape of the subject (a process called reconstruction).
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] If color information is collected at each point, then the colors and textures on the surface of the subject can also be determined.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] 3D scanners share several traits with cameras.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Like most cameras, they have a cone-like field of view, and like cameras, they can only collect information about surfaces that are not obscured.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] While a camera collects color information about surfaces within its field of view, a 3D scanner collects distance information about surfaces within its field of view.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The "picture" produced by a 3D scanner describes the distance to a surface at each point in the picture.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] This allows the three dimensional position of each point in the picture to be identified.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] In some situations, a single scan will not produce a complete model of the subject.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Multiple scans, from different directions are usually helpful to obtain information about all sides of the subject.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] These scans have to be brought into a common reference system, a process that is usually called *alignment* or *registration*, and then merged to create a complete 3D model.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] This whole process, going from the single range map to the whole model, is usually known as the 3D scanning pipeline.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] There are a variety of technologies for digitally acquiring the shape of a 3D object.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The techniques work with most or all sensor types including optical, acoustic, laser scanning, radar, thermal, and seismic.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] 3D scan technologies can be split in 2 categories: contact and non-contact.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Non-contact solutions can be further divided into two main categories, active and passive.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] There are a variety of technologies that fall under each of these categories.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Contact 3D scanners work by physically probing (touching) the part and recording the position of the sensor as the probe moves around the part.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Both modern CMMs and Articulated Arms can also be fitted with non-contact laser scanners instead of touch probes.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Active scanners emit some kind of radiation or light and detect its reflection or radiation passing through object in order to probe an object or environment.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Possible types of emissions used include light, ultrasound or x-ray.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The time-of-flight 3D laser scanner is an active scanner that uses laser light to probe the subject.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] At the heart of this type of scanner is a time-of-flight laser range finder.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The laser range finder finds the distance of a surface by timing the round-trip time of a pulse of light.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A laser is used to emit a pulse of light and the amount of time before the reflected light is seen by a detector is measured.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Since the speed of light c is known, the round-trip time determines the travel distance of the light, which is twice the distance between the scanner and the surface.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] If t is the round-trip time, then distance is equal to $\textstyle c\!\cdot \!t/2$ .
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The accuracy of a time-of-flight 3D laser scanner depends on how precisely we can measure the t time: 3.3 picoseconds (approx.) is the time taken for light to travel 1 millimetre.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The laser range finder only detects the distance of one point in its direction of view.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Thus, the scanner scans its entire field of view one point at a time by changing the range finder's direction of view to scan different points.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The view direction of the laser range finder can be changed either by rotating the range finder itself, or by using a system of rotating mirrors.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The latter method is commonly used because mirrors are much lighter and can thus be rotated much faster and with greater accuracy.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Typical time-of-flight 3D laser scanners can measure the distance of 10,000-100,000 points every second.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Time-of-flight devices are also available in a 2D configuration.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] This is referred to as a time-of-flight camera.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Triangulation based 3D laser scanners are also active scanners that use laser light to probe the environment.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] With respect to time-of-flight 3D laser scanner the triangulation laser shines a laser on the subject and exploits a camera to look for the location of the laser dot.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Depending on how far away the laser strikes a surface, the laser dot appears at different places in the camera's field of view.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] This technique is called triangulation because the laser dot, the camera and the laser emitter form a triangle.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The length of one side of the triangle, the distance between the camera and the laser emitter is known.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The angle of the laser emitter corner is also known.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The angle of the camera corner can be determined by looking at the location of the laser dot in the camera's field of view.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] These three pieces of information fully determine the shape and size of the triangle and give the location of the laser dot corner of the triangle.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] In most cases a laser stripe, instead of a single laser dot, is swept across the object to speed up the acquisition process.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The use of triangulation to measure distances dates to antiquity.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Time-of-flight range finders are capable of operating over long distances on the order of kilometres.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] These scanners are thus suitable for scanning large structures like buildings or geographic features.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A disadvantage is that, due to the high speed of light, measuring the round-trip time is difficult and so the accuracy of the distance measurement is relatively low, on the order of millimetres.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Triangulation range finders, on the other hand, have a range of usually limited to a few meters for reasonably sized devices, but their accuracy is relatively high.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The accuracy of triangulation range finders is on the order of tens of micrometers.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Time-of-flight scanners' accuracy can be lost when the laser hits the edge of an object because the information that is sent back to the scanner is from two different locations for one laser pulse.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The coordinate relative to the scanner's position for a point that has hit the edge of an object will be calculated based on an average and therefore will put the point in the wrong place.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] When using a high resolution scan on an object the chances of the beam hitting an edge are increased and the resulting data will show noise just behind the edges of the object.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Scanners with a smaller beam width will help to solve this problem but will be limited by range as the beam width will increase over distance.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Software can also help by determining that the first object to be hit by the laser beam should cancel out the second.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] At a rate of 10,000 sample points per second, low resolution scans can take less than a second, but high resolution scans, requiring millions of samples, can take minutes for some time-of-flight scanners.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The problem this creates is distortion from motion.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Since each point is sampled at a different time, any motion in the subject or the scanner will distort the collected data.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Thus, it is usually necessary to mount both the subject and the scanner on stable platforms and minimise vibration.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Using these scanners to scan objects in motion is very difficult.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Recently, there has been research on compensating for distortion from small amounts of vibration and distortions due to motion and/or rotation.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Short-range laser scanners can not usually encompass a depth of field more than 1 meter.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] When scanning in one position for any length of time slight movement can occur in the scanner position due to changes in temperature.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] If the scanner is set on a tripod and there is strong sunlight on one side of the scanner then that side of the tripod will expand and slowly distort the scan data from one side to another.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Some laser scanners have level compensators built into them to counteract any movement of the scanner during the scan process.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] In a conoscopic system, a laser beam is projected onto the surface and then the immediate reflection along the same ray-path are put through a conoscopic crystal and projected onto a CCD.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The result is a diffraction pattern, that can be frequency analyzed to determine the distance to the measured surface.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The main advantage with conoscopic holography is that only a single ray-path is needed for measuring, thus giving an opportunity to measure for instance the depth of a finely drilled hole.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Hand-held laser scanners create a 3D image through the triangulation mechanism described above: a laser dot or line is projected onto an object from a hand-held device and a sensor (typically a charge-coupled device or position sensitive device) measures the distance to the surface.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Data is collected in relation to an internal coordinate system and therefore to collect data where the scanner is in motion the position of the scanner must be determined.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The position can be determined by the scanner using reference features on the surface being scanned (typically adhesive reflective tabs, but natural features have been also used in research work) or by using an external tracking method.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] External tracking often takes the form of a laser tracker (to provide the sensor position) with integrated camera (to determine the orientation of the scanner) or a photogrammetric solution using 3 or more cameras providing the complete six degrees of freedom of the scanner.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Both techniques tend to use infrared light-emitting diodes attached to the scanner which are seen by the camera(s) through filters providing resilience to ambient lighting.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Data is collected by a computer and recorded as data points within three-dimensional space, with processing this can be converted into a triangulated mesh and then a computer-aided design model, often as non-uniform rational B-spline surfaces.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Hand-held laser scanners can combine this data with passive, visible-light sensors — which capture surface textures and colors — to build (or "reverse engineer") a full 3D model.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Structured-light 3D scanners project a pattern of light on the subject and look at the deformation of the pattern on the subject.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The pattern is projected onto the subject using either an LCD projector or other stable light source.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A camera, offset slightly from the pattern projector, looks at the shape of the pattern and calculates the distance of every point in the field of view.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Structured-light scanning is still a very active area of research with many research papers published each year.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Perfect maps have also been proven useful as structured light patterns that solve the correspondence problem and allow for error detection and error correction.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The advantage of structured-light 3D scanners is speed and precision.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Instead of scanning one point at a time, structured light scanners scan multiple points or the entire field of view at once.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Scanning an entire field of view in a fraction of a second reduces or eliminates the problem of distortion from motion.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Some existing systems are capable of scanning moving objects in real-time.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A real-time scanner using digital fringe projection and phase-shifting technique (certain kinds of structured light methods) was developed, to capture, reconstruct, and render high-density details of dynamically deformable objects (such as facial expressions) at 40 frames per second.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Recently, another scanner has been developed.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Different patterns can be applied to this system, and the frame rate for capturing and data processing achieves 120 frames per second.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] It can also scan isolated surfaces, for example two moving hands.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] By utilising the binary defocusing technique, speed breakthroughs have been made that could reach hundreds to thousands of frames per second.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Modulated light 3D scanners shine a continually changing light at the subject.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Usually the light source simply cycles its amplitude in a sinusoidal pattern.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A camera detects the reflected light and the amount the pattern is shifted by determines the distance the light travelled.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Modulated light also allows the scanner to ignore light from sources other than a laser, so there is no interference.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] These techniques produce a discrete 3D volumetric representation that can be directly visualised, manipulated or converted to traditional 3D surface by mean of isosurface extraction algorithms.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Passive 3D imaging solutions do not emit any kind of radiation themselves, but instead rely on detecting reflected ambient radiation.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Most solutions of this type detect visible light because it is a readily available ambient radiation.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Other types of radiation, such as infrared could also be used.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Passive methods can be very cheap, because in most cases they do not need particular hardware but simple digital cameras.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Photogrammetry provides reliable information about 3D shapes of physical objects based on analysis of photographic images.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The resulting 3D data is typically provided as a 3D point cloud, 3D mesh or 3D points.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Various software packages are available including PhotoModeler, Geodetic Systems, Autodesk ReCap, RealityCapture and Agisoft Metashape (see comparison of photogrammetry software).
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Semi-automatic building extraction from lidar data and high-resolution images is also a possibility.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Again, this approach allows modelling without physically moving towards the location or object.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] From airborne lidar data, digital surface model (DSM) can be generated and then the objects higher than the ground are automatically detected from the DSM.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Based on general knowledge about buildings, geometric characteristics such as size, height and shape information are then used to separate the buildings from other objects.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The extracted building outlines are then simplified using an orthogonal algorithm to obtain better cartographic quality.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Watershed analysis can be conducted to extract the ridgelines of building roofs.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The ridgelines as well as slope information are used to classify the buildings per type.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The buildings are then reconstructed using three parametric building models (flat, gabled, hipped).
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Lidar and other terrestrial laser scanning technology offers the fastest, automated way to collect height or distance information. lidar or laser for height measurement of buildings is becoming very promising.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Commercial applications of both airborne lidar and ground laser scanning technology have proven to be fast and accurate methods for building height extraction.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The building extraction task is needed to determine building locations, ground elevation, orientations, building size, rooftop heights, etc.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Most buildings are described to sufficient details in terms of general polyhedra, i.e., their boundaries can be represented by a set of planar surfaces and straight lines.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Further processing such as expressing building footprints as polygons is used for data storing in GIS databases.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Using laser scans and images taken from ground level and a bird's-eye perspective, Fruh and Zakhor present an approach to automatically create textured 3D city models.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] This approach involves registering and merging the detailed facade models with a complementary airborne model.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The airborne modeling process generates a half-meter resolution model with a bird's-eye view of the entire area, containing terrain profile and building tops.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Ground-based modeling process results in a detailed model of the building facades.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Using the DSM obtained from airborne laser scans, they localize the acquisition vehicle and register the ground-based facades to the airborne model by means of Monte Carlo localization (MCL).
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Finally, the two models are merged with different resolutions to obtain a 3D model.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Using an airborne laser altimeter, Haala, Brenner and Anders combined height data with the existing ground plans of buildings.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The ground plans of buildings had already been acquired either in analog form by maps and plans or digitally in a 2D GIS.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The project was done in order to enable an automatic data capture by the integration of these different types of information.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Afterwards virtual reality city models are generated in the project by texture processing, e.g. by mapping of terrestrial images.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The project demonstrated the feasibility of rapid acquisition of 3D urban GIS.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Ground plans proved are another very important source of information for 3D building reconstruction.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Compared to results of automatic procedures, these ground plans proved more reliable since they contain aggregated information which has been made explicit by human interpretation.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] For this reason, ground plans, can considerably reduce costs in a reconstruction project.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] An example of existing ground plan data usable in building reconstruction is the Digital Cadastral map, which provides information on the distribution of property, including the borders of all agricultural areas and the ground plans of existing buildings.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Additionally information as street names and the usage of buildings (e.g. garage, residential building, office block, industrial building, church) is provided in the form of text symbols.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] At the moment the Digital Cadastral map is built up as a database covering an area, mainly composed by digitizing preexisting maps or plans.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The point clouds produced by 3D scanners and 3D imaging can be used directly for measurement and visualisation in the architecture and construction world.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Most applications, however, use instead polygonal 3D models, NURBS surface models, or editable feature-based CAD models (aka solid models).
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] These CAD models describe not simply the envelope or shape of the object, but CAD models also embody the "design intent" (i.e., critical features and their relationship to other features).
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] An example of design intent not evident in the shape alone might be a brake drum's lug bolts, which must be concentric with the hole in the centre of the drum.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] This knowledge would drive the sequence and method of creating the CAD model; a designer with an awareness of this relationship would not design the lug bolts referenced to the outside diameter, but instead, to the center.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A modeler creating a CAD model will want to include both Shape and design intent in the complete CAD model.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Vendors offer different approaches to getting to the parametric CAD model.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Some export the NURBS surfaces and leave it to the CAD designer to complete the model in CAD (e.g., Geomagic, Imageware, Rhino 3D).
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Others use the scan data to create an editable and verifiable feature based model that is imported into CAD with full feature tree intact, yielding a complete, native CAD model, capturing both shape and design intent (e.g.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] For instance, the market offers various plug-ins for established CAD-programs, such as SolidWorks.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Xtract3D, DezignWorks and Geomagic for SolidWorks allow manipulating a 3D scan directly inside SolidWorks.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Still other CAD applications are robust enough to manipulate limited points or polygon models within the CAD environment (e.g., CATIA, AutoCAD, Revit).
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] CT, industrial CT, MRI, or micro-CT scanners do not produce point clouds but a set of 2D slices (each termed a "tomogram") which are then 'stacked together' to produce a 3D representation.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The laser power used for laser scanning equipment in industrial applications is typically less than 1W.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The power level is usually on the order of 200 mW or less but sometimes more.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] 3D data acquisition and object reconstruction can be performed using stereo image pairs.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Stereo photogrammetry or photogrammetry based on a block of overlapped images is the primary approach for 3D mapping and object reconstruction using 2D images.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Close-range photogrammetry has also matured to the level where cameras or digital cameras can be used to capture the close-look images of objects, e.g., buildings, and reconstruct them using the very same theory as the aerial photogrammetry.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] An example of software which could do this is Vexcel FotoG 5.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] This software has now been replaced by Vexcel GeoSynth.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Another similar software program is Microsoft Photosynth.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A semi-automatic method for acquiring 3D topologically structured data from 2D aerial stereo images has been presented by Sisi Zlatanova.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The process involves the manual digitizing of a number of points necessary for automatically reconstructing the 3D objects.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Each reconstructed object is validated by superimposition of its wire frame graphics in the stereo model.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The topologically structured 3D data is stored in a database and are also used for visualization of the objects.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Notable software used for 3D data acquisition using 2D images include e.g.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Agisoft Metashape, RealityCapture, and ENSAIS Engineering College TIPHON (Traitement d'Image et PHOtogrammétrie Numérique).
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A method for semi-automatic building extraction together with a concept for storing building models alongside terrain and other topographic data in a topographical information system has been developed by Franz Rottensteiner.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] His approach was based on the integration of building parameter estimations into the photogrammetry process applying a hybrid modeling scheme.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Buildings are decomposed into a set of simple primitives that are reconstructed individually and are then combined by Boolean operators.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Multiple images are used in Zhang's approach to surface reconstruction from multiple images.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A central idea is to explore the integration of both 3D stereo data and 2D calibrated images.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] This approach is motivated by the fact that only robust and accurate feature points that survived the geometry scrutiny of multiple images are reconstructed in space.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The density insufficiency and the inevitable holes in the stereo data should then be filled in by using information from multiple images.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The idea is thus to first construct small surface patches from stereo points, then to progressively propagate only reliable patches in their neighborhood from images into the whole surface using a best-first strategy.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The problem thus reduces to searching for an optimal local surface patch going through a given set of stereo points from images.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Multi-spectral images are also used for 3D building detection.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The first and last pulse data and the normalized difference vegetation index are used in the process.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] New measurement techniques are also employed to obtain measurements of and between objects from single images by using the projection, or the shadow as well as their combination.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] This technology is gaining attention given its fast processing time, and far lower cost than stereo measurements.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] 3D scanning technology has been used to scan space rocks for the European Space Agency.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] 3D scanners are used by the entertainment industry to create digital 3D models for movies, video games and leisure purposes.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] They are heavily utilized in virtual cinematography.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] In cases where a real-world equivalent of a model exists, it is much faster to scan the real-world object than to manually create a model using 3D modeling software.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Frequently, artists sculpt physical models of what they want and scan them into digital form rather than directly creating digital models on a computer.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] 3D scanners are evolving for the use of cameras to represent 3D objects in an accurate manner.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Companies are emerging since 2010 that create 3D portraits of people (3D figurines or 3D selfie).
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] 3D laser scanning is used by the law enforcement agencies around the world.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Reverse engineering of a mechanical component requires a precise digital model of the objects to be reproduced.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Rather than a set of points a precise digital model can be represented by a polygon mesh, a set of flat or curved NURBS surfaces, or ideally for mechanical components, a CAD solid model.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A 3D scanner can be used to digitise free-form or gradually changing shaped components as well as prismatic geometries whereas a coordinate measuring machine is usually used only to determine simple dimensions of a highly prismatic model.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] These data points are then processed to create a usable digital model, usually using specialized reverse engineering software.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Land or buildings can be scanned into a 3D model, which allows buyers to tour and inspect the property remotely, anywhere, without having to be present at the property.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] There is already at least one company providing 3D scanned virtual real estate tours.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A typical virtual tour Archived 2017-04-27 at the Wayback Machine would consist of dollhouse view, inside view, as well as a floor plan.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The environment at a place of interest can be captured and converted into a 3D model.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] This model can then be explored by the public, either through a VR interface or a traditional "2D" interface.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] This allows the user to explore locations which are inconvenient for travel.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A group of history students at Vancouver iTech Preparatory Middle School created a Virtual Museum by 3D Scanning more than 100 artifacts.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] There have been many research projects undertaken via the scanning of historical sites and artifacts both for documentation and analysis purposes.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The resulting models can be used for a variety of different analytical approaches.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The combined use of 3D scanning and 3D printing technologies allows the replication of real objects without the use of traditional plaster casting techniques, that in many cases can be too invasive for being performed on precious or delicate cultural heritage artifacts.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] In an example of a typical application scenario, a gargoyle model was digitally acquired using a 3D scanner and the produced 3D data was processed using MeshLab.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The resulting digital 3D model was fed to a rapid prototyping machine to create a real resin replica of the original object.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] More recently, smartphone-based LiDAR apps have enabled on-site capture of cultural heritage objects; for example, a 1,500-year-old Buddhist stone relief was scanned using a LiDAR-equipped iPhone and the CapCam app, producing a high-density mesh suitable for 3D printing a physical replica.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] In 1999, two different research groups started scanning Michelangelo's statues.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Stanford University with a group led by Marc Levoy used a custom laser triangulation scanner built by Cyberware to scan Michelangelo's statues in Florence, notably the David, the Prigioni and the four statues in The Medici Chapel.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The scans produced a data point density of one sample per 0.25 mm, detailed enough to see Michelangelo's chisel marks.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] These detailed scans produced a large amount of data (up to 32 gigabytes) and processing the data from his scans took 5 months.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Approximately in the same period a research group from IBM, led by H.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Bernardini scanned the Pietà of Florence acquiring both geometric and color details.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The digital model, result of the Stanford scanning campaign, was thoroughly used in the 2004 subsequent restoration of the statue.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] In 2002, David Luebke, et al. scanned Thomas Jefferson's Monticello.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A commercial time of flight laser scanner, the DeltaSphere 3000, was used.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The scanner data was later combined with color data from digital photographs to create the Virtual Monticello, and the Jefferson's Cabinet exhibits in the New Orleans Museum of Art in 2003.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The Virtual Monticello exhibit simulated a window looking into Jefferson's Library.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The exhibit consisted of a rear projection display on a wall and a pair of stereo glasses for the viewer.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The glasses, combined with polarised projectors, provided a 3D effect.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Position tracking hardware on the glasses allowed the display to adapt as the viewer moves around, creating the illusion that the display is actually a hole in the wall looking into Jefferson's Library.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The Jefferson's Cabinet exhibit was a barrier stereogram (essentially a non-active hologram that appears different from different angles) of Jefferson's Cabinet.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The first 3D models of cuneiform tablets were acquired in Germany in 2000.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] In 2003 the so-called *Digital Hammurabi project* acquired cuneiform tablets with a laser triangulation scanner using a regular grid pattern having a resolution of 0.025 mm (0.00098 in).
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] With the use of high-resolution 3D scanners by the Heidelberg University for tablet acquisition in 2009 the development of the GigaMesh Software Framework began to visualize and extract cuneiform characters from 3D models.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] 2.000 3D digitized tablets of the Hilprecht Collection in Jena to create an Open Access benchmark dataset and an annotated collection of 3D models of tablets freely available under CC BY licenses.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A 2009 CyArk 3D scanning project at Uganda's historic Kasubi Tombs, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, using a Leica HDS 4500, produced detailed architectural models of Muzibu Azaala Mpanga, the main building at the complex and tomb of the Kabakas (Kings) of Uganda.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] A fire on March 16, 2010, burned down much of the Muzibu Azaala Mpanga structure, and reconstruction work is likely to lean heavily upon the dataset produced by the 3D scan mission.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] In 2005, Gabriele Guidi, et al. scanned the "Plastico di Roma antica", a model of Rome created in the last century.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Neither the triangulation method, nor the time of flight method satisfied the requirements of this project because the item to be scanned was both large and contained small details.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] They found though, that a modulated light scanner was able to provide both the ability to scan an object the size of the model and the accuracy that was needed.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The modulated light scanner was supplemented by a triangulation scanner which was used to scan some parts of the model.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The Smithsonian Institution has a project called Smithsonian X 3D notable for the breadth of types of 3D objects they are attempting to scan.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] These include small objects such as insects and flowers, to human sized objects such as Amelia Earhart's Flight Suit to room sized objects such as the Gunboat Philadelphia to historic sites such as Liang Bua in Indonesia.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Also of note the data from these scans is being made available to the public for free and downloadable in several data formats.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] 3D scanners are used to capture the 3D shape of a patient in orthotics and dentistry.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] It gradually supplants tedious plaster cast.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] CAD/CAM software are then used to design and manufacture the orthosis, prosthesis or dental implants.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The chairside systems are designed to facilitate the 3D scanning of a preparation *in vivo* and produce the restoration (such as a Crown, Onlay, Inlay or Veneer).
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Creation of 3D models for anatomy and biology education and cadaver models for educational neurosurgical simulations.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The digitalisation of real-world objects is of vital importance in various application domains.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] This method is especially applied in industrial quality assurance to measure the geometric dimension accuracy.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Industrial processes such as assembly are complex, highly automated and typically based on CAD (computer-aided design) data.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The problem is that the same degree of automation is also required for quality assurance.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] It is, for example, a very complex task to assemble a modern car, since it consists of many parts that must fit together at the very end of the production line.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The optimal performance of this process is guaranteed by quality assurance systems.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Especially the geometry of the metal parts must be checked in order to assure that they have the correct dimensions, fit together and finally work reliably.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Within highly automated processes, the resulting geometric measures are transferred to machines that manufacture the desired objects.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Due to mechanical uncertainties and abrasions, the result may differ from its digital nominal.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] In order to automatically capture and evaluate these deviations, the manufactured part must be digitised as well.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] For this purpose, 3D scanners are applied to generate point samples from the object's surface which are finally compared against the nominal data.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The process of comparing 3D data against a CAD model is referred to as CAD-Compare, and can be a useful technique for applications such as determining wear patterns on moulds and tooling, determining accuracy of final build, analysing gap and flush, or analysing highly complex sculpted surfaces.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] At present, laser triangulation scanners, structured light and contact scanning are the predominant technologies employed for industrial purposes, with contact scanning remaining the slowest, but overall most accurate option.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Nevertheless, 3D scanning technology offers distinct advantages compared to traditional touch probe measurements.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] White-light or laser scanners accurately digitize objects all around, capturing fine details and freeform surfaces without reference points or spray.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] The entire surface is covered at record speed without the risk of damaging the part.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Graphic comparison charts illustrate geometric deviations of full object level, providing deeper insights into potential causes.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] After the data has been collected, the acquired (and sometimes already processed) data from images or sensors needs to be reconstructed.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] This may be done in the same program or in some cases, the 3D data needs to be exported and imported into another program for further refining, and/or to add additional data.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Such additional data could be GPS-location data.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] After the reconstruction, the data might be directly implemented into a local (GIS) map or a worldwide map such as Google Earth or Apple Maps.
[src:log-splitter/3d-scanning] Several software packages are used in which the acquired (and sometimes already processed) data from images or sensors is imported.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The idea of fighting forest fires from the air dates back at least as far as Friedrich Karl von Koenig-Warthausen's observations on seeing a blaze when overflying the Santa Lucia Range, California, in 1929.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] A wide variety of terminology has been used in the popular media for the aircraft (and methods) used in aerial firefighting.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The terms **airtanker** or **air tanker** generally refer to fixed-wing aircraft based in the United States; "airtanker" is used in official documentation.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The term "**waterbomber**" is used in some Canadian government documents for the same class of vehicles, though it sometimes has a connotation of amphibians.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] A wide variety of helicopters and fixed-wing aircraft are used for aerial firefighting.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Forest Service and Bureau of Land Management own, lease, or contract for nearly 1,000 aircraft each fire season, with annual expenditures in excess of US$250 million in recent years".
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Helicopters may be fitted with tanks (helitankers) or they may carry buckets.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Some helitankers, such as the Erickson AirCrane, are also outfitted with a front-mounted foam cannon.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Buckets are usually filled by submerging or dipping them in lakes, rivers, reservoirs, or portable tanks.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The most popular of the buckets is the flexible Bambi Bucket.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Tanks can be filled on the ground (by water tenders or truck-mounted systems) or water can be siphoned from lakes, rivers, reservoirs, or a portable tank through a hanging snorkel.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Currently the world's largest helicopter, the Mil Mi-26, uses a Bambi bucket.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The Mendocino Air Tanker Squad formed by Joseph Bolles Ely in 1956 was the first such unit in the United States to drop water and retardant on fires.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Based at the Willows-Glenn County Airport it soon led the way for other agencies to form similar squads.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Though World War II- and Korean War-era bombers were for a long time the mainstay of the aerial firefighting fleet, newer purpose-built tankers have since come online.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The smallest are the Single Engine Air Tankers (SEATs).
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] These are agricultural sprayers that generally drop about 800 US gallons (3,000 L) of water or retardant.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Examples include the Air Tractor AT-802, which can deliver around 800 gallons of water or fire retardant solution in each drop, and the Soviet Antonov An-2 biplane.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Both of these aircraft can be fitted with floats that scoop water from the surface of a body of water.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Similar in configuration to the World War II–era Consolidated PBY Catalina, the Canadair CL-215 and its derivative the CL-415 are designed and built specifically for firefighting.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The Croatian Air Force uses six CL-415s as well as six AT 802s for firefighting purposes.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Conair also converted a number of Convair 580 and Fokker F27 Friendship turboprop airliners to air tankers.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The largest aerial firefighter ever used is a Boeing 747 aerial firefighter, known as the Global Supertanker, that can carry 19,600 US gallons (74,200 L) fed by a pressurized drop system.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The Supertanker was deployed operationally for the first time in 2009, fighting a fire in Spain.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The tanker made its first American operation on August 31, 2009, at the Oak Glen Fire.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] It has since been replaced by a Boeing 747-400.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Another wide body jetliner that is currently being used as an air tanker is the modified McDonnell Douglas DC-10-30 operated by the 10 Tanker Air Carrier company as the DC-10 Air Tanker.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] It can carry up to 12,000 US gallons (45,400 L) of fire fighting retardant.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The Russian Ministry of Emergency Situations operates convertible-to-cargo Ilyushin Il-76 airtankers that have been operating with 11,000-US-gallon (41,600 L) tanking systems, and several Beriev Be-200 jet powered amphibian aircraft.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The Be-200 can carry a maximum payload of about 12,000 litres (3,200 US gal) of water, making "scoops" in suitable stretches of water in 14 seconds.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Bombardier's Dash 8 Q Series aircraft are the basis of new, next-generation air tankers.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Cascade Aerospace has converted two pre-owned Q400s to act as part-time water bomber and part-time transport aircraft for France's Sécurité Civile, while Neptune Aviation is converting a pre-owned Q300 as a prototype to augment its Lockheed P-2 Neptune aircraft.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The Sécurité Civile also operates twelve Canadair CL-415 and nine Conair Turbo Firecat aircraft.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Neptune Aviation also currently operates converted British Aerospace 146 jetliners as air tankers.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The BAe 146 can carry up to 3,000 gallons of fire fighting retardant.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Air Spray USA Ltd. of Chico, California has also converted the BAe 146 jetliner to the role of air tanker.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Another modern-era passenger aircraft that has now been converted for aerial firefighting missions in the U.S. is the McDonnell Douglas MD-87 jetliner operated by Erickson Aero Tanker.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The MD-87 can carry up to 4,000 gallons of fire fighting retardant.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Coulson Aviation unveiled a Boeing 737-300 firefighting conversion in May 2017.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Six aircraft have been purchased from Southwest Airlines for the RADS system conversion which was planned to enter service in December 2017.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The 737 aircraft is smaller than the C-130Q which allows for a wider range of airfields to be utilized.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Britt Coulson further stated the aircraft will be able to retain the current seat and galley configuration for tanker operations.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] On 22 November 2018, the 737 was used for the first time to fight a fire near Newcastle, Australia.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] In July 2022, Airbus tested the aerial firefighting capacity of the A400M using a roll-on/roll-off kit comprising a 20-tonne water tank and piping allowing the load to be expelled from the end of the cargo ramp.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] All links, citations and data sources are listed in the paragraph above.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] For accident and grounding citations, see paragraph below table.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Other former military aircraft utilized as firefighting air tankers in the U.S. in the past included the B-17 and the PB4Y-2, a version of the B-24.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The Lead Plane function directs the activities of the airtankers by both verbal target descriptions and by physically leading the airtankers on the drop run.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The leadplane is typically referred to as a "Bird Dog" in Canada or "Supervision" aircraft in Australia.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The O-2 Skymaster, Cessna 310 and OV-10 Bronco have been used as spotter and lead plane platforms.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources has also used the Cessna 337.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The Beechcraft Baron was long used as a leadplane or air attack ship, but most were retired in 2003; more common now is the Beechcraft King Air and the Twin Commander 690.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] A Cessna Citation 500 jet owned by Air Spray (1967) LTd. was used by the British Columbia Ministry of Forests beginning in 1995 and used for two fire seasons to lead the very fast Electra L188 air tanker to the fires.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] This was the first time a jet aircraft was used as a lead plane or "bird dog".
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The Department of Parks and Wildlife in Western Australia operates a fleet of nine American Champion Scouts 8GCBC during the summer months as spotter aircraft and Air Attack platforms.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The Provinces of Alberta and British Columbia and the Yukon Territories contract to supply Twin Commander 690 as bird dog aircraft for their air tanker fleets.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Air Spray owns 9 Twin Commander 690 for use as bird dog aircraft.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] In the United States, most of these aircraft are privately owned and contracted to government agencies, and the National Guard and the U.S.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Marines also maintain fleets of firefighting aircraft.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Forest Service (USFS) and the Bureau of Land Management (BLM) announced that they were cancelling contracts with operators of 33 heavy airtankers.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] They cited liability concerns and an inability to safely manage the fleet after the wing failure and resulting crash of a C-130A Hercules in California and a PB4Y-2 in Colorado during the summer of 2002.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Both aged aircraft broke up in flight due to catastrophic fatigue cracks at the wing roots.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] After subsequent third-party examination and extensive testing of all USFS contracted heavy airtankers, three companies were awarded contracts and now maintain a combined fleet of 23 aircraft.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Borate salts used in the past to fight wildfires have been found to sterilize the soil and be toxic to animals so are now prohibited.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Newer retardants use ammonium sulfate or ammonium polyphosphate with attapulgite clay thickener or diammonium phosphate with a guar gum derivative thickener.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Fire retardants often contain wetting agents, preservatives and rust inhibitors and are colored red with ferric oxide or fugitive color to mark where they have been dropped.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Brand names of fire retardants for aerial application include Fortress and Phos-Chek.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Some water-dropping aircraft carry tanks of a guar gum derivative to thicken the water and reduce runoff.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Helicopters can hover over the fire and drop water or retardant.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The S-64 Helitanker has microprocessor-controlled doors on its tank.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] The doors are controlled based on the area to be covered and wind conditions.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Fixed-wing aircraft must make a pass and drop water or retardant like a bomber.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Water is not usually dropped directly on flames because its effect is short-lived.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Fire retardants are not typically used to extinguish the fire, but instead are used to contain the fire, or slow it down to allow ground crews to contain it.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Because of this, retardants are usually dropped in front of or around a moving fire, rather than directly on it, creating a firebreak.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Aerial firefighting is most effectively used in conjunction with ground-based efforts, as aircraft are only one weapon in the firefighting arsenal.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] However, there have been cases of aircraft extinguishing fires long before ground crews were able to reach them.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] Some firefighting aircraft can refill their tanks in mid-flight, by flying down to skim the surface of large bodies of water.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] This is particularly useful in rural areas where flying back to an airbase for refills may take too much time.
[src:log-splitter/aerial-firefighting] In 2002 an Ontario CL-415 crew was able to refill 100 times within a 4-hour mission, delivering 162,000 US gallons (613,240 L) or 1,350,000 pounds (612 t) of water on a fire near Dryden, Ontario (June 1, 2002 Dryden fire # 10 Tanker #271 civil ident C-GOGE).
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means re-establishing forest that have either been cut down or lost due to natural causes, such as fire, storm, etc.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Nowadays, the boundaries between afforestation and reforestation projects can be blurred as it may not be so clear what was there before at what point in time.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] An essential aspect of successful afforestation efforts lies in the careful selection of tree species that are well-suited to the local climate and soil conditions.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] By choosing appropriate species, afforested areas can better withstand the impacts of climate change.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Planting and protecting them would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon which is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's current carbon pool.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] However, there has been debate about whether afforestation is beneficial for the sustainable use of natural resources, with some researchers pointing out that tree planting is not the only way to enhance climate mitigation and CO2 capture.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Non-forest areas, such as grasslands and savannas, also benefit the biosphere and humanity, and they need a different management strategy - they are not supposed to be forests.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Afforestation critics argue that ecosystems without trees are not necessarily degraded, and many of them can store carbon as they are; for example, savannas and tundra store carbon underground.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Carbon sequestration estimates in these areas often do not include the total amount of carbon reductions in soils and slowing tree growth over time.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Afforestation can also negatively affect biodiversity by increasing fragmentation and edge effects on the habitat outside the planted area.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Australia, Canada, China, India, Israel, United States and Europe have afforestation programs to increase carbon dioxide removal in forests and in some cases to reduce desertification.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The term afforestation means establishing new forest on lands that were not forest before (e.g. abandoned agriculture).
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The same definition in other words states that afforestation is "conversion to forest of land that historically has not contained forests".
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means the "conversion to forest of land that has previously contained forests but that has been converted to some other use".
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Agroforestry (this is essentially an agricultural activity carried out in order to grow harvestable crops such as fruits and nuts).
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Tree plantations (carried out in order to produce wood and wood-pulp products; this can be seen as an alternative to cutting down naturally occurring forests).
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] However, the term *afforestation* can also "imply the intentional conversion of native non-forest ecosystems to exotic tree cover and violate biodiversity safeguards".
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The process of afforestation begins with site selection.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Several environmental factors of the site must be analyzed, including climate, soil, vegetation, and human activity.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] These factors will determine the quality of the site, what species of trees should be planted, and what planting method should be used.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] After the forest site has been assessed, the area must be prepared for planting.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Preparation can involve a variety of mechanical or chemical methods, such as chopping, mounding, bedding, herbicides, and prescribed burning.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Once the site is prepared, planting can take place.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] One method for planting is direct seeding, which involves sowing seeds directly into the forest floor.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Another is seedling planting, which is similar to direct seeding except that seedlings already have an established root system.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Afforestation by cutting is an option for tree species that can reproduce asexually, where a piece of a tree stem, branch, root, or leaves can be planted onto the forest floor and sprout successfully.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Sometimes special tools, such as a tree planting bar, are used to make planting of trees easier and faster.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] There are several benefits from afforestation such as carbon sequestration, increasing rainfall, prevention of topsoil erosion (from water and wind), flood and landslide mitigation, barriers against high winds, shelter for wildlife, employment and alternative sources of wood products.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Afforestation projects create employment opportunities, particularly in rural areas, thus promoting sustainable livelihoods.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] They can create many jobs in various forest-related activities.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Forests are an important part of the global carbon cycle because trees and plants absorb carbon dioxide through photosynthesis.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Therefore, they play an important role in climate change mitigation.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] By removing the greenhouse gas CO2 from the air, forests function as terrestrial carbon sinks, meaning they store large amounts of carbon in the form of biomass, encompassing roots, stems, branches, and leaves.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] By doing so, forests sequester approximately 25% of human carbon emissions annually, playing a critical role in Earth's climate.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Throughout their lifespan, trees continue to sequester carbon, storing atmospheric CO2 long-term.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Sustainable forest management, afforestation, reforestation are therefore important contributions to climate change mitigation.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] An important consideration in such efforts is that forests can turn from sinks to carbon sources.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In 2019 forests took up a third less carbon than they did in the 1990s, due to higher temperatures, droughts and deforestation.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] National-scale forest inventory data also shows trends from 1999 to 2020 that some forests were already approaching climate thresholds shifting them from carbon sinks to carbon sources.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The typical tropical forest may become a carbon source by the 2060s.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Researchers have found that, in terms of environmental services, it is better to avoid deforestation than to allow for deforestation to subsequently reforest, as the latter leads to irreversible effects in terms of biodiversity loss and soil degradation.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Furthermore, the probability that legacy carbon will be released from soil is higher in a younger boreal forest.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In particular, boreal forests have been noted to support the growth of Armillaria (honey fungus), which is a root pathogen that breaks down compounds necessary for wood integrity, increasing the likelihood of carbon release.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Global greenhouse gas emissions caused by damage to tropical rainforests may have been substantially underestimated until around 2019.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Additionally, the effects of afforestation and reforestation will be farther in the future than keeping existing forests intact.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] It takes much longer − several decades − for the benefits for global warming to manifest to the same carbon sequestration benefits from mature trees in tropical forests and hence from limiting deforestation.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Therefore, scientists consider "the protection and recovery of carbon-rich and long-lived ecosystems, especially natural forests" to be "the major climate solution".
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The planting of trees on marginal crop and pasture lands helps to incorporate carbon from atmospheric CO 2 into biomass.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] For this carbon sequestration process to succeed the carbon must not return to the atmosphere from biomass burning or rotting when the trees die.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Several species of *Ficus* such as *Ficus wakefieldii* have been observed to sequester atmospheric CO2 as calcium oxalate in the presence of oxalotrophic bacteria and fungi, which catabolize the oxalate, which produces calcium carbonate.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The calcium carbonate is precipitated throughout the tree, which also alkalinizes the surrounding soil.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] These species are current candidates for carbon sequestration in agroforestry.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] This Calcium-oxalate fixation process was first observed in the *Iroko* tree, which can sequester up to a ton of calcium carbonate in the soil over its lifespan.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Also Cacti, such as the *Saguaro*, transfer carbon from the biological cycle to the geological cycle by forming the mineral calcium carbonate.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover, although this estimate has been criticized, and the true area that has a net cooling effect on the climate when accounting for biophysical feedbacks like albedo is 20-80% lower.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Planting and protecting these trees would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon if the trees survive future climate stress to reach maturity.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] To put this number into perspective, this is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions (as of 2019) .
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's carbon pool in 2019.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Life expectancy of forests varies throughout the world, influenced by tree species, site conditions, and natural disturbance patterns.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In some forests, carbon may be stored for centuries, while in other forests, carbon is released with frequent stand replacing fires.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Forests that are harvested prior to stand replacing events allow for the retention of carbon in manufactured forest products such as lumber.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] However, only a portion of the carbon removed from logged forests ends up as durable goods and buildings.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The remainder ends up as sawmill by-products such as pulp, paper, and pallets.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] If all new construction globally utilized 90% wood products, largely via adoption of mass timber in low rise construction, this could sequester 700 million net tons of carbon per year.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] This is in addition to the elimination of carbon emissions from the displaced construction material such as steel or concrete, which are carbon-intense to produce.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] A meta-analysis found that mixed species plantations would increase carbon storage alongside other benefits of diversifying planted forests.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Although a bamboo forest stores less total carbon than a mature forest of trees, a bamboo plantation sequesters carbon at a much faster rate than a mature forest or a tree plantation.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Therefore, the farming of bamboo timber may have significant carbon sequestration potential.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that: "The total carbon stock in forests decreased from 668 gigatonnes in 1990 to 662 gigatonnes in 2020".
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In Canada's boreal forests as much as 80% of the total carbon is stored in the soils as dead organic matter.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Impacts on temperature are affected by the location of the forest.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] For example, reforestation in boreal or subarctic regions has less impact on climate.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] This is because it substitutes a high-albedo, snow-dominated region with a lower-albedo forest canopy.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] By contrast, tropical reforestation projects lead to a positive change such as the formation of clouds.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] These clouds then reflect the sunlight, lowering temperatures.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Planting trees in tropical climates with wet seasons has another advantage.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In such a setting, trees grow more quickly (fixing more carbon) because they can grow year-round.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Trees in tropical climates have, on average, larger, brighter, and more abundant leaves than non-tropical climates.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] A study of the girth of 70,000 trees across Africa has shown that tropical forests fix more carbon dioxide pollution than previously realized.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The research suggested almost one-fifth of fossil fuel emissions are absorbed by forests across Africa, Amazonia and Asia.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Afforestation provides other environmental benefits, including increasing the soil quality and its organic carbon levels, reducing the risk of erosion and desertification.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The planting of trees in urban areas is also able to reduce air pollution via the trees' absorption and filtration of pollutants, including carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide, and ozone, in addition to CO2.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Afforestation protects the biodiversity of plants and animals which allows the sustenance of ecosystems that provide clean air, soil fertilization, etc.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Forests support biodiversity conservation, providing habitats for about 80% of the world's biodiversity and contributing to ecosystem restoration and resilience.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Water management can be improved afforestation, as trees regulate hydrological cycles, reduce soil erosion, and prevent water runoff.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Their capacity to capture and store water helps in mitigating floods and droughts.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Forests act as natural air filters, absorbing pollutants and improving air quality.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Urban forestation projects have been successful in reducing respiratory illnesses and enhancing overall air quality in cities.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Trees provide shade and cooling effects.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] By shading and evaporation, forests can lower local temperatures, offering a more comfortable environment in urban areas and reducing the impact of extreme heat.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Tree-planting campaigns are criticised for sometimes targeting areas where forests would not naturally occur, such as grassland and savanna biomes.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Carbon sequestration forecasts of afforestation programmes often insufficiently consider possible carbon reductions in soils as well as slowing tree growth over time.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Afforestation can negatively affect biodiversity through increasing fragmentation and edge effects for the habitat remaining outside the planted area.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] New forest plantations can introduce generalist predators that would otherwise not be found in open habitat into the covered area, which could detrimentally increase predation rates on the native species of the area.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] A study by scientists at the British Trust for Ornithology into the decline of British populations of Eurasian curlew found that afforestation had impacted curlew populations through fragmentation of their naturally open grassland habitats and increases in generalist predators.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Questions have also been raised in the scientific community regarding how global afforestation could affect the surface albedo of Earth.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The canopy cover of mature trees could make the surface albedo darker, which causes more heat to be absorbed, potentially raising the temperature of the planet.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] This is particularly relevant in parts of the world with high levels of snow cover, due to the significant difference in albedo between highly reflective white snow and darker forest cover which absorbs more solar radiation.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] One significant criticism of reforestation or afforestation efforts that rely on monocultures of - usually conifer - trees is that, while they may increase tree cover, they fail to provide the diverse and complex habitat needed by most woodland creatures.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Monocultures, often planted for commercial purposes or ease of management, lack the biodiversity of natural forests.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] These single-species forests provide limited food sources, shelter, and nesting sites for a wide range of wildlife, and in purely coniferous forests low levels of light may reach the forest floor reducing habitat and variety of plant life.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Many woodland creatures, such as birds, mammals, and insects, rely on a variety of tree species and plant life for survival, and the uniformity of monocultures does not support these varied ecological needs.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] As a result, such reforestation or afforestation efforts may unintentionally create environments that are unsuitable for the very species they aim to protect, thus undermining broader conservation goals.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The Great Green Wall of Africa is a ~5,000 mile forest being planted across the continent to stop the spread of the Sahara Desert to the south.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In Adelaide, South Australia (a city of 1.3 million as of June 2016), Premier Mike Rann (2002 to 2011) launched an urban forest initiative in 2003 to plant 3 million native trees and shrubs by 2014 on 300 project sites across the metro area.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Thousands of Adelaide citizens participated in community planting days on sites including parks, reserves, transport corridors, schools, water courses and coastline.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Only native trees were planted to ensure genetic integrity.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Rann said the project aimed to beautify and cool the city and make it more livable, improve air and water quality, and reduce Adelaide's greenhouse gas emissions by 600,000 tonnes of CO2 per year.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In 2003, the government of Canada created a four-year project called the Forest 2020 Plantation Development and Assessment Initiative, which involved planting 6000 ha of fast-growing forests on non-forested lands countrywide.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] These plantations were used to analyze how afforestation can help to increase carbon sequestration and mitigate greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions while also considering the economic and investment attractiveness of afforestation.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] On 14 December 2020, Canada's Minister of Natural Resources Seamus O'Regan announced the federal government's investment of $3.16 billion to plant two billion trees over the next 10 years.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] This plan aims to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by an estimated 12 megatonnes by 2050.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] China had the highest afforestation rate of any country or region in the world, with 4.77 million hectares (47,000 square kilometers) of afforestation in 2008.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] According to the 2021 government work report, forest coverage will reach 24 percent based on the main targets and tasks for the 14th Five-Year Plan period.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] A law in China from 1981 requires that every school student over the age of 11 plants at least one tree per year.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] From 2011 to 2016, the city Dongying in Shandong province forested over 13,800 hectares of saline soil through the Shandong Ecological Afforestation Project, which was launched with support from the World Bank.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In 2017, the Saihanba Afforestation Community won the UN Champions of the Earth Award in the Inspiration and Action category for "transforming degraded land into a lush paradise".
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The successful afforestation of the Loess Plateau involved collaborative efforts by international and domestic professionals alongside villagers.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Through this initiative, millions of villagers across four of China's poorest provinces were able to improve farming practices and increase incomes and employment, alleviating poverty.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In addition, the careful selection of trees ensured a healthy, self-sustainable ecosystem between tree and soil which facilitated a net carbon sink.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The Loess Plateau, although successful, was costly, reaching almost US$500 million.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] This contrasts with more recent initiatives where the results have not been as favorable.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In an attempt to make afforestation both low-cost and less time-consuming, China shifted towards monoculture of mostly red pine trees.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] However, this did not adequately take into consideration environmental structure and led to increased soil erosion, desertification, sand/dust storms and short-lived trees.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] This has reduced China's environmental sustainability index (ESI) to one of the lowest in the world.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Regarding the effects of afforestation on long-term carbon stocks and carbon sequestration these decrease when trees are less than 5 years old and increase quickly thereafter.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] This means trees from monoculture planting that do not survive never reach full potential for carbon sequestration to offset China's carbon output.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Overall, there is a possibility for afforestation to balance carbon levels and aid carbon neutrality, but several challenges still remain which hinder an all encompassing effort.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The Chinese government requires mining companies to restore the environment around exhausted mines by refilling excavated pits and planting crops or trees.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Many mining companies use these recovered mines for ecotourism business.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Europe deforested more than half of its forested areas over the last 6000 years.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The European Union (EU) has paid farmers for afforestation since 1990, offering grants to turn farmland into forest and payments for the management of forest.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] As part of the Green Deal, the EU program "3 Billion Tree Planting Pledge by 2030" provides direction on afforestation of previous farmland in addition to reforestation.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] According to Food and Agriculture Organization statistics, Spain had the third fastest afforestation rate in Europe in the 1990–2005 period, after Iceland and Ireland.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In those years, a total of 44,360 square kilometers were afforested, and the total forest cover rose from 13.5 to 17.9 million hectares.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In 1990, forests covered 26.6% of the Spanish territory.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] As of 2007, that figure had risen to 36.6%.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Spain today has the fifth largest forest area in the European Union.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] As of 2023 the total forest and tree cover in India was 22%.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The forests of India are grouped into 5 major categories and 16 types based on biophysical criteria.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] 38% of the forest is categorized as subtropical dry deciduous and 30% as tropical moist deciduous and other smaller groups.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In 2016 the Indian government passed the CAMPA (Compensatory Afforestation Fund Management and Planning Authority) law, allowing about 40 thousand crores rupees (almost $6 Billion) to go to Indian states for planting trees.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In 2016 the Maharashtra government planted almost 20,000,000 saplings and pledged to plant another 30,000,000 the following year.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In 2019, 220 million trees were planted in a single day in the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] With wood production as a main objective, monocultures of Aleppo pine were vigorously planted between 1948 and the 1970s.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Following a massive collapse of this species in the 1990s, due to attacks by the insect pine blast scale, the Aleppo pine was gradually replaced by Pinus brutia.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Since the 1990s there has been a trend towards more ecological approaches planting mixed forests combining pines with broadleaf Mediterranean species e.g. oak, pistachio, carob, olive, arbutus and buckthorn.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] About 250 million trees have been planted through the JNF across Israel since 1990.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Tree coverage increased from 2% in 1948 to over 8% at present.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The Japanese temperate rainforest is well sustained and maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] One method that has been utilized in maintaining the health of forests in Japan has been afforestation.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The Japanese government and private businesses have set up multiple projects to plant native tree species in open areas scattered throughout the country.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] This practice has resulted in shifts in forest structure and a healthy temperate rainforest that maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In January 2013, the UK government set a target of 12% woodland cover in England by 2060, up from the then 10%.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In Wales the National Assembly for Wales has set a target of 19% woodland cover, up from 15%.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Government-backed initiatives such as the Woodland Carbon Code are intended to support this objective by encouraging corporations and landowners to create new woodland to offset their carbon emissions.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Charitable groups such as Trees for Life (Scotland) contribute to afforestation and reforestation efforts in the UK.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Afforestation efforts in Scotland have provided an increase in woodland expansion.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] By the 20th century mark, Scotland had diminished woodland coverage to 5% of Scotland's land area.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] However, by the early 21st century, afforestation efforts have increased woodland coverage to 17%.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The Scottish government released their Draft Climate Change Plan in January 2017.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] The 2017 draft plan has increased the targeted woodland coverage to 21% by 2032 and increases the afforestation rate to 15,000 hectares per year.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] In the 1800s people moving westward in the US encountered the Great Plains – land with fertile soil, a growing population and a demand for timber but with few trees to supply it.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] So tree planting was encouraged along homesteads.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Arbor Day was founded in 1872 by Julius Sterling Morton in Nebraska City.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] By the 1930s the Dust Bowl environmental disaster signified a reason for adding significant new tree cover.
[src:log-splitter/afforestation] Public works programs under the New Deal saw the planting of 18,000 miles of windbreaks stretching from North Dakota to Texas to fight soil erosion (see Great Plains Shelterbelt).
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] An **angle gauge** is a tool used by foresters to determine which trees to measure when using a variable radius plot design in forest inventory.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] Using this tool a forester can quickly measure the trees that are in or out of the plot.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] An angle gauge is similar to a wedge prism though it must be held a fixed distance from the eye to work properly.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] Unlike the wedge prism, which is held over the plot center, the surveyor's eye is kept over plot-center when using an angle gauge.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] When using an angle gauge the user must count trees that are larger than the width of the angle gauge, as viewed from the center of the plot.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] The angle gauge is held a set distance from the eye of the surveyor.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] Most angle gauges have a string or chain that lets the user know the set distance.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] Each angle gauge is set at a certain basal area factor (BAF).
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] Each tree that is in the plot represents this number, the BAF, of square footage.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] It is multiplied by the number of trees on the plot to give basal area per acre.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] In the United States BAF is measured in units of square feet.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] For example, using a BAF 10 angle gauge a forester measures 12 trees that are *in* trees.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] Therefore, this plot represents 120 sq ft/acre (28 m2/ha).
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] Some trees are on the borderline of the plot and must be checked to be sure they are to be included.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] The limiting distance must be calculated to see if the trees are *in* or *out*.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] The equation to calculate the limiting distance in feet is diameter at breast height, DBH, in inches times plot radius factor, PRF, in feet/area Dlim = DBH×PRF.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] For example, using a BAF 10 angle gauge a forester needs to know the limiting distance for a 20-inch (510 mm) tree.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] The PRF using a 10 BAF angle gauge is 2.75 feet (0.84 m) for every inch of tree diameter.
[src:log-splitter/angle-gauge] This means that a 20-inch (510 mm) tree must be over 55 feet (17 m) away from the center of the plot using a BAF 10 angle gauge to be out of the plot.
[src:log-splitter/axe] An **axe** (/æks/; sometimes spelled **ax** in American English; see spelling differences) is an implement that has been used for thousands of years to shape, split, and cut wood, to harvest timber, and as a weapon.
[src:log-splitter/axe] The axe has many forms and specialised uses but generally consists of a head with a sharpened blade (also called a "bit") attached to a handle (also called "haft" or "helve").
[src:log-splitter/axe] Before the modern axe, the stone-age hand axe without a handle was used from 1.5 million years BP.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Hafted axes (those with a handle) date from at least 46,000 years BP by Northern Indigenous Australians.
[src:log-splitter/axe] The earliest examples of handled axes have heads of stone with some form of wooden handle attached (hafted) in a method to suit the available materials and use.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Axes made of copper, bronze, iron and steel appeared as these technologies developed.
[src:log-splitter/axe] The axe is an example of a simple machine, as it is a type of wedge, or dual inclined plane.
[src:log-splitter/axe] This reduces the effort needed by the wood chopper.
[src:log-splitter/axe] It cuts and splits the wood into two parts by the pressure concentration at the blade and then the movement of the head in behind the initial cut.
[src:log-splitter/axe] The handle of the axe also acts as a lever allowing the user to increase the force at the cutting edge.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Generally, the blades of 'cutting axes', which are used for felling, limbing, and bucking, have a shallow (acute) wedge angle, whereas 'splitting axes' have a deeper (more obtuse) angle.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Most axes are double bevelled (i.e. symmetrical about the axis of the blade), but some specialist broadaxes have a single bevel blade.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Most modern axes have steel heads and wooden handles, although plastic or fibreglass handles are also common.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Modern axes are specialised by use, size and form.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Hafted axes with short handles designed for use with one hand are often called "hand axes", but the term "hand axe" can also refer to an axe without a handle.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Hatchets tend to be short-, small-hafted axes often with a hammer on the back side (the poll, or butt).
[src:log-splitter/axe] Relatively easy to make and use, the axe has frequently been used in combat, and is one of humanity's oldest weapons.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Axes are also linchpins to the competitive sport of wood-chopping.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Hand axes, of stone, and used without handles (hafts) were the first axes.
[src:log-splitter/axe] They had knapped (chipped) cutting edges of flint or other stone.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Early examples of hand axes date back to 1.6 mya in the later Oldowan, in Southern Ethiopia around 1.4 mya, and in 1.2 mya deposits in Olduvai Gorge.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Hafted axes are first known from the Mesolithic period (c.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Few wooden hafts have been found from this period, but it seems that the axe was normally hafted by wedging.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Birch-tar and rawhide lashings were used to fix the blade.
[src:log-splitter/axe] The distribution of stone axes is an important indication of prehistoric trade.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Thin sectioning is used to determine the provenance of the stone blades.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Stone axes are still produced and in use today in parts of Papua, Indonesia.
[src:log-splitter/axe] The Mount Hagen area of Papua New Guinea was an important production centre.
[src:log-splitter/axe] From the late Neolithic/Chalcolithic onwards, axes were made of copper or copper mixed with arsenic.
[src:log-splitter/axe] These axes were flat and hafted much like their stone predecessors.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Axes continued to be made in this manner with the introduction of bronze metallurgy.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Eventually the hafting method changed and the flat axe developed into the "flanged axe", then palstaves, and later winged and socketed axes.
[src:log-splitter/axe] At least since the late Neolithic, elaborate axes (battle-axes, T-axes, etc.) had a religious significance and probably indicated the exalted status of their owner.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Certain types almost never show traces of wear; deposits of unshafted axe blades from the middle Neolithic (such as at the Somerset Levels in Britain) may have been gifts to the deities.
[src:log-splitter/axe] In Minoan Crete, the double axe (labrys) had a special significance, used by priestesses in religious ceremonies.
[src:log-splitter/axe] In 1998, a labrys, complete with an elaborately embellished haft, was found at Cham-Eslen, Canton of Zug, Switzerland.
[src:log-splitter/axe] The haft was 120 cm (47 in) long and wrapped in ornamented birch-bark.
[src:log-splitter/axe] The axe blade is 17.4 cm (6.9 in) long and made of antigorite, mined in the Gotthard-area.
[src:log-splitter/axe] The haft goes through a biconical drilled hole and is fastened by wedges of antler and by birch-tar.
[src:log-splitter/axe] It belongs to the early Cortaillod culture.
[src:log-splitter/axe] The coat of arms of Norway features a lion rampant carrying an axe which represents King Olaf II of Norway, who was honoured as the Eternal King of Norway.
[src:log-splitter/axe] In folklore, stone axes were sometimes believed to be thunderbolts and were used to guard buildings against lightning, as it was believed (mythically) that lightning never struck the same place twice.
[src:log-splitter/axe] This has caused some skewing of axe distributions.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Steel axes were important in superstition as well.
[src:log-splitter/axe] A thrown axe could keep off a hailstorm, sometimes an axe was placed in the crops, with the cutting edge to the skies to protect the harvest against bad weather.
[src:log-splitter/axe] An upright axe buried under the sill of a house would keep off witches, while an axe under the bed would assure male offspring.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Basques, Australians and New Zealanders have developed variants of rural sports that perpetuate the traditions of log cutting with axe.
[src:log-splitter/axe] The Basque variants, splitting horizontally or vertically disposed logs, are generically called *aizkolaritza* (from *aizkora*: axe).
[src:log-splitter/axe] In Yorùbá mythology, the oshe (double-headed axe) symbolises Shango, Orisha (god) of thunder and lightning.
[src:log-splitter/axe] It is said to represent swift and balanced justice.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Shango altars often contain a carved figure of a woman holding a gift to the god with a double-bladed axe sticking up from her head.
[src:log-splitter/axe] The Hurrian and Hittite weather god Teshub is depicted on a bas-relief at Ivriz wielding a thunderbolt and an axe.
[src:log-splitter/axe] The Arkalochori Axe is a bronze Minoan axe from the second millennium BC thought to be used for religious purposes.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Inscriptions on this axe have been compared with other ancient writing systems.
[src:log-splitter/axe] In Mark Masonry, the axe is a symbol of punishment meant to remind Mark Master Masons to be truthful and avoid deceit.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Hammer axes (or axe-hammers) typically feature an extended poll, opposite the blade, shaped and sometimes hardened for use as a hammer.
[src:log-splitter/axe] The name axe-hammer is often applied to a characteristic shape of perforated stone axe used in the Neolithic and Bronze Ages.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Iron axe-hammers are found in Roman military contexts, e.g.
[src:log-splitter/axe] Cramond, Edinburgh, and South Shields, Tyne and Wear.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] A **billhook** or **bill hook** is a versatile cutting tool used widely in agriculture and forestry for cutting woody material such as shrubs, small trees and branches.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] It was commonly used in Europe with an important variety of traditional local patterns.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Elsewhere, it was also developed locally such as in the Indian subcontinent, or introduced regionally as in the Americas, South Africa, and Oceania by European settlers.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The blade is usually made from a medium-carbon steel in varying weights and lengths, but typically 20 to 25 centimetres (7.9 to 9.8 in) long.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Blades are straight near the handle but have an increasingly strong curve towards the end.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The blade is generally sharpened only on the inside of the curve, but double-edged billhooks, or "broom hooks", also have a straight secondary edge on the back.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The blade is fixed to a wooden handle, in Europe usually made from ash due to its strength and ability to deal with repeated impact.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Handles are mostly 12 to 15 centimetres (4.7 to 5.9 in) long and may be "caulked" or round.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] ("Caulked" handles have a knob sticking out on one side at the bottom of the handle, intended to help keep the tool from slipping out of your hand.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] See sidebar.) Longer handles are sometimes used for heavier patterns, making the tool double-handed.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The blade and handle are usually linked by a tang passing through the handle, but sometimes a socket that encloses the blade.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Some styles of billhook have scales of hardwood or horn fitted to the handle.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Some billhooks (for example the Kent pattern) have a single-bevelled blade, available in both right- and left-handed versions, others (such as the Machynlleth pattern) have dished blades (concave one side and convex the other), or a pronounced thickened nose (such as the Monmouth pattern).
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The reasons for many of these variations are now lost.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The use of a billhook is between that of a knife and an axe.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] It is often used for cutting woody plants such as saplings and small branches, for hedging and for snedding (stripping the side shoots from a branch).
[src:log-splitter/billhook] In France and Italy it is widely used for pruning grape vines.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The billhook is the European equivalent of tools such as machetes, parangs, and kukris.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Prior to the advent of chainsaws, billhooks were used to clear brush and undergrowth from around the base of a tree that was to be felled by either axe or crosscut saw.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The billhook's use as a cutting tool goes back to the Bronze Age, and a few examples survive from this period, for example, found in the sea around Greece.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Iron examples from the later Iron Age have been found in pre-Roman settlements in several English counties, as well as in France and Germany, where it is called "Hippe" or "Sechsle", and Switzerland, where it is called "Gertel".
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The tool has developed a large variety of names in different parts of Britain, including bill, hedging bill, hand bill, hook bill, billhook, billook, brushing hook and broom hook.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] In American English a billhook may sometimes be called a "fascine knife".
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Made on a small scale in village smithies and in larger industrial sites, e.g.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Old Iron Works, Mells, the billhook is still relatively common throughout most of western Europe.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] During the 19th and early 20th centuries the larger manufacturers offered up to 200 or so different regional styles and shapes of blade, sometimes in a range of different sizes from 6 to 11 inches (15 to 28 cm) long in 0.5-inch (1.3 cm) steps.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The French firm of Talabot boasted in their 1930 catalogue that they held over 3000 different patterns in their archives.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Billhooks would have once been made by the local smith to the user's specifications but now sizes and shapes are largely standardised.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The handles are mostly rat-tail tang, except the Yorkshire having such a long handle that a tang is just not practical – they have a socket instead.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The smaller hooks have variations in the shape of the handle: round, oval and pistol-grip.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Billhooks are almost universally made from ordinary steel of a moderate carbon content.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] High-carbon steel is not often used since an extremely sharp and hard edge is not necessary, and a slightly lower carbon content makes the hook easier to sharpen in the field.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Hygiene and cosmetic appearance are unimportant so more expensive stainless steel is not used.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Billhooks have a relatively thick blade since they are typically used for cutting thick and woody vegetation.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The nose is sometimes also thickened to bring the sweet spot further forward and to optimise the chopping action.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The edge of a billhook is not bevelled to a very narrow angle to avoid binding in green wood.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The hooked front of the blade is designed to prevent the sharpened inner edge from hitting the ground, which would quickly damage or blunt it.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Billhooks were the tool of choice for clearing areas of brush and shrubs, since this activity requires chopping close to the ground.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] In German speaking countries, the billhook is known as a *Rodeaxt*, which translates to "clearing axe".
[src:log-splitter/billhook] A billhook may vary in shape depending from which part of the UK it originates; there are eleven main types.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Favoured by Midlands-style hedgers, this is a one handed tool with a 6-inch (15 cm) handle and a 10-inch (25 cm) blade.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] It has a curved front edge and a shorter straight edge at the back, the front edge being used for general purpose and the back edge kept extremely sharp for delicate trimming, topping off stakes and other work that will not damage the blade.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Used by a small percentage of Midlands-style hedgers, this is generally a two-handed tool with a 14-inch (36 cm) handle and 10-inch (25 cm) blade; again, it has the curved front and straight back edges.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] In some cases the handle can be up to 36 inches (91 cm) long.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The disadvantage of this variety of tool is its weight.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Have a 9-inch (23 cm) handle and a 10-inch (25 cm) blade.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Have a 6-inch (15 cm) handle and a 10-inch (25 cm) blade, but lack the back edge or the hedge grip of the Llandeilo.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] With similar measurements to the Pontypool/Monmouthshire style, this style has the least curvature of any hook and is almost a straight blade.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Has slightly more curvature than the Knighton.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The top picture shows a Newtown pattern billhook.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The southern group of hedgers use hooks often designed for other woodland work besides hedging.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] They are all single-edged and vary from moderately heavy to very light.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Has a heavily weighted nose, a 6-inch (15 cm) handle and a 10-inch (25 cm) blade.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Slightly lighter than the Devon with a bulge in the middle that accentuates the curve further up the hook.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] It has the same measurements as the Devonshire.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Lighter again than the Bristol with its much more traditional shape and identical measurements to the Devonshire.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Very light with a 6-inch (15 cm) handle and a 6-to-7-inch (15 to 18 cm) blade.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Too light to be used for snedding of anything except the smallest of side-shoots, its main use is the splitting of spars (or spits or broaches, depending upon the region), made from hazel gads for use by thatchers in pegging down the layers of thatch.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Often found with a small hook at the back of the blade – useful for pulling the wood towards the user.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] A variety of other hooks were also made by most edge-tool makers, including pea and bean hooks, gorse or furze hooks, trimming hooks, staff hooks, slashers, pruning hooks, that are closely related to the billhook, although they may differ in shape, width or thickness of blade, length of handle, etc.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] For example, a slasher has a long handle.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Another very close relation is the meat cleaver – sizes and handle-fixing of these are often very similar to billhooks.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] In some other European countries the same name is used for both tools, and it can be difficult to identify whether the tool is intended for cutting wood or animal bones.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Usage of billhooks also varies from country to country – in Sweden they were often used for cutting fodder for livestock, whereas in the UK a gorse or furze hook would have been used.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] In France and Italy they were widely used for pruning vines (only recently has wine making come back to the UK), and miniature billhooks were used for harvesting grapes during the *vendange* in France.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] In the Netherlands they were often used in a carpenter's workshop (in the UK use of a small hand axe was more common), and they were also found in the coopers' workshops in France, where they were known as a cochoir, and used in the making of wooden barrel hoops.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] In the Balkans they were used for harvesting maize.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] In Finland they are used to cut branches from trees and cutting down small trees, known as *vesuri*.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Images of billhooks often appear on coats of arms of towns and villages, particularly in winemaking areas of Alsace, the Black Forest, Hungary and Switzerland, and have been found carved into boundary stones in parts of Germany and onto rock faces in Italy.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Billhooks are currently in common use by thatchers, coppicers, agricultural hurdle makers, charcoal burners and often by other traditional craftsmen, bushcraft, farmers and woodsmen.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] They are also the primary tool for hedgelayers.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] In the French Republican calendar, February 8 was named *Serpette* "Billhook".
[src:log-splitter/billhook] In the medieval period a weapon similar to the halberd was called a bill or billhook.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] It consisted of a pole with a bill-like blade mounted below a spearhead, with spikes added to the back of the blade to increase the versatility of the weapon against cavalry and armour.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The English, in particular, were known for using massed billmen rather than pikes or halberds in the Renaissance period, notably at the Battle of Flodden in 1513, when the Scottish king James IV was felled by an arrow and bill.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] The billhook is an issued tool in some armed forces (see fascine knife).
[src:log-splitter/billhook] It is used for cutting brushwood for making fascines (brushwood bundles) and gabions – originally for the construction of cannon emplacements, and later for machine gun emplacements.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] It is also issued to the pioneer corps of most regiments.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] In the Indian Army, it is given the name "knife gabion".
[src:log-splitter/billhook] A non-military use as a weapon was a "pruning bill", described as the weapon used in the Pierre Rivière parricide case of 1835.
[src:log-splitter/billhook] Finnish military engineer NCOs have a billhook as the part of their personal gear instead of an entrenching tool.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] The **Biltmore stick** is a tool used by foresters to estimate tree trunk diameter at breast height.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] The tool very often includes a hypsometer scale to estimate height as well.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] It looks much like an everyday yardstick.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] With practice a Biltmore stick is considered to be exceptionally accurate, often within half an inch on diameters.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] However, many prefer to use more accurate tools such as a diameter tape or tree caliper to measure diameter at breast height (DBH), and a clinometer to measure height.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] On the other end of the spectrum, some foresters consider the use of a Biltmore stick to be no more accurate than their own visual estimates (based on experience estimating the height and DBH of trees), and make it practice for their surveys to be largely completed in this manner.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] The Biltmore stick uses the principle of similar triangles.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] Similar triangles involve using identical angles but different side lengths.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] Diameter at breast height (DBH) is measured by holding the stick a fixed distance, usually 25 inches (64 cm), from the eye, and at breast height, which in the United States is 4.5 feet (1.4 m) up the bole of the tree.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] The left side of the stick is flush with the left side of the tree.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] The number where the right side of the tree lines up with the stick is the approximate DBH of the tree.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] To measure height, the user stands a fixed distance from the tree, usually 66 feet (20 m) in the United States.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] The stick is held upright, with the back edge of the stick facing the user.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] The back edge of the stick will be marked with 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5 log markings, indicating the number of 16-foot (4.9 m) logs in a tree.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] The bottom of the stick should line up with the bottom of the tree's trunk.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] The height of the tree is how high the tree goes up on the stick to a merchantable top.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] Tree height is measured to a merchantable top, the point at which a tree can be accepted for use by a sawmill.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] This point can be reached either by defects (extreme sweep, crook, deviating branching, or other defects) or at a diameter limit for very straight trees.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] A common cutoff is 4 inches (10 cm) diameter, which is acceptable for pulpwood.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] The Biltmore stick is so named because it was developed at the Biltmore Estate, one of the first places in the United States where forestry was applied as a science.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] Gifford Pinchot, the future first chief of the United States Forest Service, and then Carl A.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] Schenck were hired in the 1890s to restore 125,000 acres (510 km2) of land around the Biltmore estate to a healthy forest.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] Schenck was the developer of the Biltmore stick.
[src:log-splitter/biltmore-stick] Ever since that time, the Biltmore stick has been used by foresters to quickly cruise timber.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] A **log splitter** is a piece of machinery or equipment used for splitting firewood from softwood or hardwood logs that have been pre-cut into sections (rounds), usually by chainsaw or on a saw bench.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Many log splitters consist of a hydraulic pump or electric motor which then powers a hydraulic or electrical rod and piston assembly.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Generally, these are often rated by the tons of force they can generate.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] The higher the force rating, the greater the thickness or length of the rounds that can be split.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] The log splitter consists of all four major hydraulic components.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Most log splitter models for home use have a rating of around 10 tons, but professional hydraulic models may exert 30 tons of force or more.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] There are also manual log splitters, which use mechanical leverage to force logs through a sharpened blade assembly; and screw or 'corkscrew' types that are driven directly from an agricultural tractor's power take-off shaft where the splitter is mounted on the three-point hitch.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] A simple log splitter may be powered by an electric motor driving a hydraulic pump or by gasoline or diesel engine with or without a tractor.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] The non-electric versions can be used remotely where the splitter can be moved to the location of the cut wood source.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Split logs can then be loaded into trucks, trailers or bulk bags.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] No matter what the power source, a log splitter either uses a hydraulic piston to drive the log through a stationary blade or a rotating cone-shaped screw mandrel that pulls the log up over a wedge.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Some models have attachments that prevent the split logs from falling to the ground allowing the operator to reposition the logs quickly for a second pass on the log splitter.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Some cone or screw splitters are mounted on steel platforms mounted on a three-point hitch that allow the log to be repeatedly split into smaller pieces without putting the wood down and up again.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Although smaller firewood splitters are intended for homes, there are now many commercial units available.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Some commercial splitters are part of a 'firewood processor' that saw logs of timber into lengths, split them, and then carries the wood up an inclined conveyor onto a pile or into a bag, truck, or trailer.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Specialty producers such as those producing maple syrup use units that split 4-foot lengths.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Machines that split and point wood for fence posts also exist though they are few as it is generally safer and more convenient to see the posts.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] The rising cost of domestic heating gas oil has reawakened a desire for alternative fuel sources and burning wood is carbon-neutral.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Modern wood-burning stoves are efficient and safe.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Many consumers that would not have considered splitting their logs a few years ago are now burning wood fuel for both ecological and economical reasons.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Although a good log splitter can save the operator hours of labor, it is not possible to make it completely safe.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Only trained users should operate a log splitter since anything caught between the log and the splitting blade will be subjected to a force of at least 10 tons, while most modern wood splitters will produce 25 tons or more.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Most hydraulic machines now have 'two-handed operation' for safety which means that both of the operator's hands are needed to actuate the splitter thus keeping them out of the way of the moving blade.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] The behavior of each log cannot be predicted, so a safety zone should be established around the splitter to prevent injury from flying splinters of wood.
[src:log-splitter/log-splitter] Helpers can pick up the individual pieces of firewood, but should not stand near the log splitter while it is in operation.
